label chapter10:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden & Communal Greenhouse | Before Dawn]

    scene bg ch9_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quick, driving percussion under a rising string ostinato]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant pumps, the clack of tools, the soft murmur of volunteers organizing]
    "You ride the after-echo of the choice you made two nights ago — the rushed uplift that Ibe and you threw together when the pumps first failed. It sits in your muscles like remembered motion: bolts"
    "turned, tarps cinched, a thousand small improv stitches that kept houses from tilting into the Flats. You can still taste salt and solder."
    "The greenhouse smells like wet earth and boiled tea; steamy breath fogs the panes when you exhale. Volunteers move like a single organism below the glass: arms linked to buckets, faces grey with fatigue and focused"
    "hope. Kai barks a list of names and supplies from the loading ramp, his voice a bright cleat in the morning noise. Rosa stands at a tabletop, hands deep in a sack of cordgrass plugs, counting"
    "with the relentless calm of someone used to making things live again."
    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq is beside you, sleeves rolled, welding goggles up on his head. His hands are ink-smudged and precise. He rubs at a fresh bruise along his knuckle without stopping, as if the motion will steady him."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We bought time. Not safety — but time. Time to finish the terraces, to raise the connectors, to move people from those lowest basements."
    "You want to argue the semantics of 'bought' versus 'earned' until it becomes a fight. Instead you count the volunteers — the map of the Flats in your head — and you point."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Then we spend it. Kai, start the west-side chain; Rosa, tideplant team goes after the breach. Ibe — you and me take the block by the promenade. It’s where my mother kept the lemon tree."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "The lemon tree can wait if you won't. But I won't let you go alone."
    "The greenhouse light sharpens. Your chest tightens in the way it does when a plan becomes flesh: urgent, exact, public. There is no time for theatrical speeches. Just equipment, people, and the tasks that keep roofs above heads."
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch9_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A galvanized shout — "Move! — two straps here!" — then the steady slap of work]

    menu:
        "Hand the radio to Kai and lead the west team":
            "You hand Kai the radio. He grins and takes the role with the kind of reckless competence that steadies you. You move out with the west team, boots slapping across the greenhouse roof, your lungs filling with wet, hopeful air."
        "Stay with Ibe and finish bolting the modular connectors":
            "You stay with Ibe and the connector stack. He hands you the ratchet; the metal sings as you torque it. Close work draws you nearer in a way words never have."
        "Run to the supplies and redistribute heavier tools":
            "You sprint to the supply cribs, breath staccato. Your hands are the bridge between shortages and the people who need them; someone pats your shoulder and the world feels like it's tilting back toward right."

    menu:
        "Go with the rescue chain to the childhood block":
            "You slip into the human chain, hands slipping on muddy rope, the smell of lemon and old paint rising. Each person passes buckets, each person counts. For a fleeting half-hour, you remember being a child and then you remember why you are not one."
        "Stay and finish the flange to secure more houses":
            "You stay. The flange tightens. A dozen roofs will not tilt tonight because you kept your hands on metal. Ibe nods at you, wordless thanks linking your breath to his."
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
